  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Prosecutorial discretion is the power of prosecutors to decide whether, whom, and how to charge. It is the most consequential structural feature of the American legal system from a sociological perspective, because it determines which social conflicts enter the legal apparatus at all. The vast majority of potentially prosecutable conduct is never charged. What gets prosecuted is a product of institutional priorities, resource constraints, political pressures, and — crucially — the categories through which prosecutors perceive the social world.\n",
  "keywords": "legalism, american-law",
